      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "616ef12c_08124778",
      "file_path": "runtime-controlloop/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/clamp/controlloop/runtime/commissioning/CommissioningProvider.java",
      "patchset_number": 6,
      "line": 252,
      "message": "not sure this helps, as it appears to just re-processes the same initialNodeTypes over and over",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2021-07-28 14:39:21.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "2f418dc0_ad558d02",
      "file_path": "runtime-controlloop/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/clamp/controlloop/runtime/commissioning/CommissioningProvider.java",
      "patchset_number": 5,
      "line": 257,
      "message": "I have looked at this solution for a little while and it is nice. After implementing, I realised that it does not deal with the case where a node type with a derived_from type that has not been added to the filtered array yet is processed. It results in these sub-types being skipped unless they are \"looped through\" in the correct order (which cannot be guaranteed).\n\nThe solution I had, loops through the intialNodeTypes array several times yes but this is to ensure that all these types are added - even if they are not in a particular order.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 7603,
        "name": "Saul Gill",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "saul.gill@est.tech",
        "username": "saul.gill"
      },
      "updated": "2021-07-28 16:36:56.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "c8b763e9_e5a93269",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "54b9d86c_b02e493b",
      "file_path": "runtime-controlloop/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/clamp/controlloop/runtime/commissioning/CommissioningProvider.java",
      "patchset_number": 6,
      "line": 252,
      "message": "As mentioned in the previous comment, I do this to ensure that there are not types skipped due to the fact that their derived_from types have not been added to the filteredNodeTypes yet. note that the filtered node types are needed because they represent those node types that have common properties associated with them.\n\nThis does not cause duplication of entry into the filteredNodeTypes either as the putIfAbsent method is employed.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 7603,
        "name": "Saul Gill",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "saul.gill@est.tech",
        "username": "saul.gill"
      },
      "updated": "2021-07-28 16:36:56.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "616ef12c_08124778",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "76fa51e7_8f9a7d78",
      "file_path": "runtime-controlloop/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/clamp/controlloop/runtime/commissioning/CommissioningProvider.java",
      "patchset_number": 6,
      "line": 252,
      "message": "I don't see any merging happening here, as lines 259-262 simply make a copy of the derivedFrom type's properties.  Merging of properties can be done by creating a copy of the derivedFrom's properties and invoking putAll to add the current type's properties to the copy.  This avoids the need for the forEach on line 262.\n\nAlso, it looks to me like if initial only contained one node and filtered contained a hierarchy of 3+ types, then the properties of the types in filtered would not be merged into the types further down; only those found in initial would be merged down.\n\nAn alternative to using this O(N^2) loop would be to use a recursive function that looks up a given [derivedFrom] type in filterNodes and, not finding that, looks it up in initialNodes.  In the former case, it would simply return the properties that it found.  In the latter case, it would build the merged properties for the new type.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2021-07-28 20:50:58.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "54b9d86c_b02e493b",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "d49e73d8_7a6321e9",
      "file_path": "runtime-controlloop/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/clamp/controlloop/runtime/commissioning/CommissioningProvider.java",
      "patchset_number": 6,
      "line": 252,
      "message": "Hi Jim.\n\nI have added the changes you suggested for 259-262. Thanks for that.\n\nFor the second paragraph of your comment, filtered will never contain more than initial. Initial is a list of all node types. At the start filtered is a list of those node types that have common properties associated with them and a \"Root\" type. Filtered is added to with derived types yes but will never be bigger than initial.\n\nI take your point on the recursion. Is it possible to leave this for a review when I come back from leave?",
